3) You have an InventoryService wich has HashMap<String, Number> serviceHitsMap;
But while accessing serviceHitsMap and updating it, it seems someday inconsistency.
What is the root cause and probable/recommended  fixes?

HashMap Data Inconsistency in InventoryService — Root Cause & Fix

HashMap is not thread-safe.
In a Spring Service (singleton by default), multiple threads concurrently read/write serviceHitsMap → race conditions.

@Service
public class InventoryService {

    // ❌ PROBLEM: Shared mutable state — not thread-safe
    private HashMap<String, Number> serviceHitsMap = new HashMap<>();

    public void recordHit(String serviceKey) {
        Number count = serviceHitsMap.get(serviceKey);     // Thread-1 reads: 5
        serviceHitsMap.put(serviceKey, count.intValue() + 1); // Thread-2 reads: 5
        // Both write 6 — one update LOST
    }
}


✅ Fix 1 — ConcurrentHashMap + AtomicInteger (Recommended)
@Service
public class InventoryService {

    // ✅ Thread-safe map + atomic counters
    private final ConcurrentHashMap<String, AtomicInteger> serviceHitsMap
                                         = new ConcurrentHashMap<>();

    public void recordHit(String serviceKey) {
        // computeIfAbsent is atomic — no race on initialization
        serviceHitsMap
            .computeIfAbsent(serviceKey, k -> new AtomicInteger(0))
            .incrementAndGet(); // ← Atomic increment, no lost updates
    }

    public int getHits(String serviceKey) {
        AtomicInteger counter = serviceHitsMap.get(serviceKey);
        return counter != null ? counter.get() : 0;
    }

    public Map<String, Integer> getAllHits() {
        Map<String, Integer> snapshot = new HashMap<>();
        serviceHitsMap.forEach((k, v) -> snapshot.put(k, v.get()));
        return snapshot;
    }
}
ConcurrentHashMap uses segment-level locking (Java 8+: CAS + bin-level sync)
AtomicInteger.incrementAndGet() is a single atomic CPU instruction (no lock needed)
computeIfAbsent is atomic — prevents duplicate key initialization


✅ Fix 2 — ConcurrentHashMap.merge() (Cleaner, Java 8+)
@Service
public class InventoryService {

    private final ConcurrentHashMap<String, Integer> serviceHitsMap
                                         = new ConcurrentHashMap<>();

    public void recordHit(String serviceKey) {
        // merge() is atomic — handles init + increment in one step
        serviceHitsMap.merge(serviceKey, 1, Integer::sum);
    }

    // Safe iteration — ConcurrentHashMap snapshot semantics
    public void printAllHits() {
        serviceHitsMap.forEach((key, count) ->
            log.info("Service: {}, Hits: {}", key, count)
        );
    }
}

✅ Fix 3 — LongAdder for High-Contention Counters (Best throughput)

@Service
public class InventoryService {

    // LongAdder beats AtomicInteger under HIGH contention
    private final ConcurrentHashMap<String, LongAdder> serviceHitsMap
                                         = new ConcurrentHashMap<>();

    public void recordHit(String serviceKey) {
        serviceHitsMap
            .computeIfAbsent(serviceKey, k -> new LongAdder())
            .increment(); // Internally stripes counters across CPU cores
    }

    public long getHits(String serviceKey) {
        LongAdder adder = serviceHitsMap.get(serviceKey);
        return adder != null ? adder.sum() : 0L;
    }
}






